\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 2: QR and orthogonal bases (10+5+10+(5+5+5) pts)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $A=QR$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $B=RQ=Q^{*}AQ=Q^{-1}AQ$
\end_inset

 is a similarity transformation, and hence has the same eigenvalues as shown
 in the book.
 Numerically (and as explained in class and in lecture 28), doing this repeatedl
y for a Hermitian 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (the unshifted QR algorithm) converges to a diagonal matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 of the eigenvalues in descending order.
 To get the eigenvectors, we observe that if the 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 matrices from each step are 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{2}$
\end_inset

, and so on, then we are computing 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdots Q_{2}^{*}Q_{1}^{*}AQ_{1}Q_{2}\cdots=\Lambda$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $A=Q\Lambda Q^{*}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=Q_{1}Q_{2}\cdots$
\end_inset

.
 By comparison to the formula for diagonalizing 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 are the eigenvectors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We perform the QR factorization of the 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times(n+1)$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $(A,\vec{b})$
\end_inset

 to form 
\begin_inset Formula \[
B=(A,\vec{b})=\hat{Q}'\hat{R}'=(\hat{Q},\hat{q}_{b})\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\hat{R} & \vec{c}\\
0 & \gamma\end{array}\right)=(\hat{Q}\hat{R},\hat{Q}\vec{c}+\gamma\hat{q}_{b}),\]

\end_inset

where the 0's arise because 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}'$
\end_inset

 is upper-triangular.
 By inspection, 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\hat{Q}\hat{R}$
\end_inset

, so the first 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}'$
\end_inset

 give 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}$
\end_inset

 and the upper-left 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 corner of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}'$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Also by inspection, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}=\hat{Q}\vec{c}+\gamma\hat{q}_{b}$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}^{*}\vec{b}=\vec{c}$
\end_inset

 (since 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{q}_{b}$
\end_inset

 must be 
\begin_inset Formula $\perp$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}$
\end_inset

).
 Hence, the first 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 entries in the last column of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}'$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}^{*}\vec{b}$
\end_inset

 as desired.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

There is one wrinkle: what happens if 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}$
\end_inset

 is linearly dependent on the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

? i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}\in C(A)$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $A\vec{x}=\vec{b}$
\end_inset

 problem has an exact solution.
 In this case, the QR factorization must break down in the last step, so
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{q}_{b}$
\end_inset

 is (at best) some arbitrary vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\perp\hat{Q}$
\end_inset

 or (at worst) infinities or NaN's.
 It doesn't matter, however, since we don't actually use 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{q}_{b}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}=\hat{Q}\vec{c}$
\end_inset

 in this case, and so we can still solve 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}\vec{x}=\vec{c}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
An easy way to approach this problem is to look at the explicit construction
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 via the Gram-Schmidt algorithms.
 By inspection, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{ij}=q_{i}^{*}v_{j}$
\end_inset

 is zero if 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is even and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is odd or vice-versa.
 Because of this, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 will have a checkerboard pattern of nonzero values: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{R}=\left(\begin{array}{cccccccc}
\times &  & \times &  & \times &  & \times\\
 & \times &  & \times &  & \times &  & \times\\
 &  & \times &  & \times &  & \times\\
 &  &  & \times &  & \times &  & \times\\
 &  &  &  & \times &  & \times\\
 &  &  &  &  & \times &  & \times\\
 &  &  &  &  &  & \times\\
 &  &  &  &  &  &  & \times\end{array}\right).\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

